{{Infobox royalty |name =Hambir Malla Dev |image= |caption= |succession =49th king of the [[Mallabhum]] |coronation = |reign =1565 - 1620 CE. |predecessor =[[Dhari Malla]] |successor =[[Dhari Hambir Malla Dev]] |religion = [[Hinduism]] |position = }} '''Hambir Malla Dev''', also known as '''Bir Hambir'''('''Beera Hambeera''') & '''Veer Hambir''', was the forty-ninth king of the [[Mallabhum]].He ruled from 1565 to 1620 CE.{{Sfn|Dasgupta|2009|p=36}}<ref name=Malabhum>Malabhum, Bishnupur-Chandra, Manoranjan; 2004; Kolkata. Deys Publishing {{ISBN|8129500442}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mallik|first1=Abhaya Pada|title=History of Bishnupur-Raj: An Ancient Kingdom of West Bengal|date=1921|publisher=Calcutta|pages=129|edition=the University of Michigan|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=QF4dAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>
==Personal life== Hambir was the 49th ruler of the [[Mallabhum|Malla dynasty]] who flourished around 1586 AD and ruled in 16th-17th century, and was a contemporary of the [[Mughal emperor]] [[Akbar]]. He fought on the side of Akbar against the [[Afghan]]s and paid an annual tribute to the Muslim viceroys of Bengal and thus acknowledged their suzerainty.<ref name=omalley>O’Malley, L.S.S., ICS, ''Bankura'', ''Bengal District Gazetteers'', pp. 21-46, first published 1908, 1995 reprint, Government of West Bengal</ref>
Bir Hambir was a pious man who started following [[Vaishnavism]]. A story in two Vaishnava works (Prem-vilasa of Nityananda Das (alias Balaram Das) and Bhakti Ratnakara of Narahari Chakrabarti) recounts the manner in which Srinivasa and other devotees were robbed by Bir Hambir while travelling from [[Vrindavan]] to [[Gauḍa (city)|Gaur]] with a number of Vaishanava manuscripts. However, Bir Hambir was so moved by Srinivasa’s reading of [[Bhagavata]] that he converted to Vaishnavism and gave Srinivasa a rich endowment of land and money. He introduced the worship of [[Madan Mohan]] to [[Bishnupur, Bankura|Bishnupur]].<ref name=omalley />
===Dev Title=== During his regime (1565 to 1620), Dev title was suffixed after title Malla and Mallabhum was very safe and secured.{{Sfn|Dasgupta|2009|p=22}}
==Rashmancha== [[File:Bishnupur Rashmancha.jpg|300px|right]] The Rashmancha is a historical building located at Bishnupur. It was commissioned by Malla king Bir Hambir in 1600 CE. During the Vaishnava Ras festival, all the Radha Krishna idols of Bishnupur town used to be brought here to be worshipped by the citizens.<ref>{{cite web|title= Bishnupur Sub-division |url=http://bankura.gov.in/Tourism/Bishnupur.htm#Rashmancha|website=bankura.gov.in|accessdate=|}}</ref>
==Dal Madal Kaman (Cannon)== [[File:Dalmadal Canon.jpg|300px|left]] During the reign of Bir Hambir the Dal Madal, one of the largest-bored cannons even made, was founded, demonstrating the skill of artisans of that time.<ref>{{cite web|title= Bishnupur Sub-division |url=http://bankura.gov.in/Tourism/Bishnupur.htm#Dalmadal_Cannon|website=bankura.gov.in|accessdate=|}}</ref> Dal Madal was made by Jagannath Karmakar. "Dal Madal" means "destruction of enemy".{{Sfn|Dasgupta|2009|p=55}}
{|class="wikitable" align="center" width="30%" style="font-size:90%; border:2px solid orange;" |+ Dal Madal Kaman (Cannon) or Dala Mardana |width="40%" align="center" valign="center"|[[File:Dalmadal Arnab Dutta 2011.JPG|150px]] |width="40%" align="center" valign="center"|[[File:Dalmadal Cannon, Bishnupur.JPG|150px]] |width="40%" align="center" valign="center"|[[File:Dalmadal Cannon, Bishnupur 2.JPG|150px]] |width="40%" align="center" valign="center"|[[File:DALMADAL.JPG|150px]] |- |valign="top"| Left Side of Kaman |valign="top"| Front Side of Kaman |valign="top"| Right Side of Kaman |valign="top"| Back Side of Kaman |- |}
