{{About|the horse|other uses|Black Jack (disambiguation)}}
[[File:JFKcapitolNov25'63.jpg|thumb|right|Black Jack in John F. Kennedy's funeral procession]] A coal-black [[Morgan horse|Morgan]]-[[American Quarter Horse]] cross, '''Black Jack''' served in the Caisson Platoon of the [[3d United States Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)|3rd U.S. Infantry Regiment (The Old Guard)]]. Named in honor of [[General of the Armies]] [[John J. Pershing|John J. "Black Jack" Pershing]], he was the [[riderless horse]] in more than 1,000 Armed Forces [[Full Honors Funeral]]s (AFFHF), the majority of which were in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. With boots reversed in the [[stirrup]]s, he was a symbol of a fallen leader.
== Early life == Black Jack was foaled January 19, 1947, and came to [[Fort Myer]] from the [[cavalry]] remount station at [[Fort Reno (Oklahoma)|Fort Reno]], [[Oklahoma]], on November 22, 1952. Black Jack was the last of the [[Quartermaster]]–issue horses branded with the Army's U.S. brand (on the left shoulder) and his Army serial number 2V56 (on the left side of his neck).<ref name="army-caisson"> {{cite web | url = http://www.army.mil/info/organization/unitsandcommands/commandstructure/theoldguard/specplt/caisson.htm | title = The Old Guard - 1/3 Battalion HHC Caisson Platoon | publisher = Army.mil | date = | accessdate = 2010-04-28 }}</ref>
== Career == Black Jack served a long and respectable military career. Among the highlights were that he participated in four [[state funeral]]s:<ref name="army-caisson" />
* [[President of the United States|Presidents]]: ** [[State funeral of John F. Kennedy|John F. Kennedy]] (1963)<ref name="MDW"/> ** [[Herbert Hoover]] (1964)<ref name="MDW"/> ** [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] (1973)<ref name="MDW">{{cite news|last=Elsen|first=William A.|title=Ceremonial Group Had Busy 5 Weeks|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 25, 1973|page=D3}}</ref> * [[Five-star general]]: ** [[Douglas MacArthur]] (1964)<ref name="MDW"/>
Army Major General [[Philip C. Wehle]] was the Commanding General of the [[United States Army Military District of Washington|Military District of Washington]] during those state funerals, except during the Presidency of Lyndon Johnson. At that time Army Major General James Adamson served as Commanding General.
== Death and burial == Black Jack died after a 29-year military career on February 6, 1976. He was cremated, with his remains laid to rest in a plot at [[Fort Myer]], [[Virginia]], on Summerall Field; his final resting place lies 200 feet (60&nbsp;m) northeast of the [[flag]]pole in the southeast corner of the [[parade]] field. He is one of four horses in [[United States]] history to be buried with [[military funeral|Full Military Honors]], the others being [[Chief (horse)|Chief]], [[Sergeant Reckless]], and [[Comanche (horse)|Comanche]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Belcher|first=Nancy Hoyt|url=http://www.aaa.com/aaa/006/EnCompass/2004/jun/jun_GuardingHistory.html|title=Guarding History and Tradition|journal=EnCompass|volume=78|number=4|date=July–August 2004}}</ref><ref>https://www.artbycrane.com/horse_history_articles_tales/cavalryhorse.html</ref>
