{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox rugby league biography |name = Jim Abercrombie |fullname = |nickname = |image = Jim Abercrombie 1908.jpg |imagesize = 100px |caption = |birth_date = 1880 |birth_place = [[South Australia]], [[Australia]] |death_date = 1948 |height = |weight = |position = {{rlp|LK}} |club1 = Wests |year1start = 1908 |year1end = 13 |appearances1 = 14 |tries1 = 0 |goals1 = 5 |fieldgoals1 = 0 |points1 = 10 |teamA = Australia |yearAstart = 1908 |yearAend = 09 |appearancesA = 2 |triesA = 0 |goalsA = 0 |fieldgoalsA = 0 |pointsA = 0 |updated = |source = <ref>[http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/jim-abercrombie/summary.html Rugby League Project]</ref><ref>[http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile_Jim-Abercrombie_508.aspx Yesterday's Hero]</ref> }}
'''Jim Abercrombie''' (born "James Maskell" (1880-1948)<ref name="encyc">{{cite book| last1=Whiticker|first1=Alan|last2=Hudson|first2=Glen|title=The Encyclopedia of Rugby League Players - Wests Tigers|year=2005|publisher=''Bas Publishing''|location=[[Melbourne, Victoria]]|isbn=1-920910-61-1|page=7}}</ref>) was an [[Australia]]n [[rugby league]] footballer who played for the [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests Magpies]] in the [[New South Wales Rugby League premiership]] competition. He also played [[rugby union]] for North Sydney and Glebe.<ref name="encyc" /> His position of choice was at [[Lock Forward|lock forward]] though his versatility meant he could play anywhere in the forwards and he often goal kicked.
==Background== Abercrombie was born as James Maskell in [[South Australia]]. [[File:Kangaroos 1908.jpg|left|thumb|500px|Abercrombie front far left with a group of the [[1908–09 Kangaroo tour of Great Britain|1908 Kangaroos]]]] ==Career== He originally played rugby union prior to the formation of the New South Wales Rugby League premiership in 1908 and was one of the original players to make the switch to the newly formed code. He attended the founding meeting of the Western Suburbs rugby league club and was elected to the inaugural committee. Abercrombie played in Wests' very first match against Balmain and scored Wests' very first goals in 1st grade in the following match against Souths. He played all nine matches of the [[1908 NSWRFL season|inaugural season]] and was selected the first [[Australian national rugby league team|national representative side]] that played against the visiting New Zealand [[1907–1908 New Zealand rugby tour of Australia and Great Britain|All Golds]]. He was also controversially a member of the [[1908–09 Kangaroo tour of Great Britain]] after he was originally left out of the squad though after a public outcry over his omission he was called in, thus making him the first international player to come from the Western Suburbs club. He played in two Tests and 30 tour matches of the long campaign.
Abercrombie was awarded Life Membership of the [[New South Wales Rugby League]] in 1914.<ref>Referee, Sydney.''Life Members of the NSW Rugby League.'' 13/05/1914 (page 12)</ref>
In 2008 the Western Suburbs Magpies celebrated their centenary by inducting six inaugural members into the club's Hall of Fame. These six included Jim Abercrombie.<ref>{{cite web |last=westsmagpies.net |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Western Suburbs Magpies Hall of Fame |work=Wests Archives |publisher=Western Suburbs Magpies R.L.F.C |year=2008 |url=http://www.westsmagpies.net/archives/2008/php/wests_halloffame.php |doi= |accessdate=2009-11-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014054601/http://www.westsmagpies.net/archives/2008/php/wests_halloffame.php |archivedate=14 October 2008 |df= }}</ref>
